      <div xml:id="NA73-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu celaviṉ kuṟippaṟintu vēṟuppaṭṭa talaivi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE said who was changed when she understood [his] intention of going.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA73">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vēṉiṉ murukkiṉ viḷaituṇa raṉṉa</l>
<l>            māṇā virala valvāyp pēey</l>
<l>            mallaṉ mūtūr malarppali yuṇīiya</l>
<l>            maṉṟam pōḻum puṉkaṇ mālait</l>
<l>            tammoṭu mañcu nammiva ṇoḻiyac </l>
<l>            celpa veṉpa tāmē cevvari</l>
<l>            mayirnirait taṉṉa vārkōl vāṅkukatirc</l>
<l>            cennelañ ceṟuvi ṉaṉṉan tuñcum</l>
<l>            pūkkeḻu paṭappaic cāykkāṭ ṭaṉṉaveṉ</l>
<l>            ṉutalkavi ṉaḻikkum pacalaiyu </l>
<l>            mayalōr tūṟṟu mampalu murittē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In sorrowful evening,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when a strong-mouthed evil spirit</l>
<l rend="indent">with fingers ugly like the ripening bunches</l>
<l rend="indent">of the silk-cotton tree in summer, crosses the village common<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṉṟam</term> is explained here by T.V.G. (this time, however, without naming a source) as a ruined building.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">to eat the offering of flowers in the fertile old village</l>
<l>he himself says he will go<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">celpa eṉpa</term>: because of the double verb form and because of <term xml:lang="ta">tāmē</term>, it seems best to take <term xml:lang="ta">eṉpa</term> not in its usual meaning as a general saying, but as referring to HIS words. There are parallels for the pl. in <term xml:lang="ta">-pa</term> used as a honorific.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that we<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nam ... oḻiya</term>: why the oblique? Actually we cannot but expect <term xml:lang="ta">nām</term>, nominative, since the transitive form of <term xml:lang="ta">oḻi</term> would be <term xml:lang="ta">oḻippa</term>.</note> stay behind here, fearing for him.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ammoṭu</term>: here the sociative simply seems to mark the indirect object of <term xml:lang="ta">añcum</term>.</note></l>
<l>It is fit for pallor, that destroys the beauty of my forehead,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as if showing<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cāykāṭṭu</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a place name (as a tertium for HER beauty), but it is possible to translate it literally.</note> the brilliance of a flowered garden,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the white birds are sleeping in the fields of red paddy,</l>
<l rend="indent2">bowing ears on long stems as hair put straight into red lines,</l>
<l>and for rumours too, that the neighbours spread.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
